The '''[[Adverse]] Childhood [[Experiences]] (ACEs) Movement''' is a set of [[grassroots]] initiatives developing [[interventions]] and "tests of change" to reduce the incidence and societal effects of [[Adverse Childhood Experiences Study|Adverse Childhood Experiences]] and to promote healing from these experiences.

The ACEs Movement arose out of the need for a [[bidirectional effort]] to create a public health change, with both [[individuals]] and institutions/ government systems. The individual is essential, because change is on the individual level is [[self-directed]]. The [[Non-governmental organization|institutions]] and government systems engagement is essential, because without the structure surrounding individuals changing, the very systems that are intended to help, can perpetuate the cycle of trauma.

Dr. Sandra Bloom's book "[[Destroying Sanctuary]]" states in its introduction that 17th century philosophers like [[René Descartes|Descartes]] took apart the person and "turned over the body to physicians and the mind to philosophers and clergy," and in the ACEs movement society is now trying to bring them back together.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ofzdFRgzxpUC&pg=PR3&q=descartes|title=Destroying Sanctuary: The Crisis in Human Service Delivery Systems|last=Bloom|first=Sandra L.|last2=Farragher|first2=Brian|date=2010-10-28|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199830848|language=en}}</ref>

ACE Nashville uses the acronym to stand for All Children Excel and is trying to raise awareness about adverse childhood experiences in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Weight of Adverse Childhood Experiences |url=https://www.nashvillescene.com/news/features/article/21018793/the-weight-of-adverse-childhood-experiences |accessdate=31 August 2018 |publisher=Nashville Scene |date=23 August 2018}}</ref>

