{{About|the phrase}}

"'''Hair of the dog'''", short for "'''Hair of the dog that bit you'''", is a [[colloquialism|colloquial]] expression in the English language  predominantly used to refer to [[alcohol]] that is consumed with the aim of lessening the effects of a [[hangover]].

==Etymology==
The expression originally referred to a method of treatment of a [[rabies|rabid]] dog bite by placing hair from the dog in the bite wound.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medterms.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=26229 |title=Hair of the dog definition - Medical Dictionary definitions of popular medical terms easily defined on MedTerms |publisher=Medterms.com |date=2012-06-14 |accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref> [[Ebenezer Cobham Brewer]] writes in the ''[[Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and Fable|Dictionary of Phrase and Fable]]'' (1898): "In [[Scotland]] it is a popular belief that a few hairs of the dog that bit you applied to the wound will prevent evil consequences. Applied to drinks, it means, if overnight you have indulged too freely, take a glass of the same wine within 24 hours to soothe the nerves. 'If this dog do you bite, soon as out of your bed, take a hair of the tail the next day.'"  He also cites two [[apocrypha]]l poems containing the phrase, one of which is attributed to  [[Aristophanes]]. It is possible that the phrase was used to justify an existing practice, as the idea of  "like cures like" ({{lang-la|[[similia similibus curantur]]}}) dates back at least to the time of [[Hippocrates]]. It exists today as the basic postulate of [[homeopathy|classical homeopathy]]. In the 1930s cocktails known as [[Corpse Reviver]]s were served in hotels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smallscreennetwork.com/video/434 |title=Corpse Reviver #2 Cocktail - The Cocktail Spirit with Robert Hess - Small Screen™ Cocktail Recipes, Bartending and Mixology and Cooking Videos |publisher=Smallscreennetwork.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref>

The earliest known reference to the phrase "hair of the dog" in connection with drunkenness is found in a text from ancient [[Ugarit]] dating from the mid to late second millennium BC,  in which the god ʾIlu becomes hungover after a drinking binge. The text includes a recipe for a salve to be applied to the god's forehead, which consists of "hairs of a dog" and parts of an unknown plant mixed with olive oil.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pardee|first1=Dennis|title=ʾIlu On A Toot (Context of Scripture 1.97)|date=1997|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004106189|pages=304–5|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/context-of-scripture/ilu-on-a-toot-1-97-aCOSB_1_97|accessdate=November 7, 2014}}</ref>

An early example of modern usage (''poil de ce chien'') can be found in [[François Rabelais|Rabelais]]' 16th century pentology [[Gargantua and Pantagruel]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Rabelais|first=|title=La Vie de Gargantua et Pantagruel Book 5|url=https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=PRxnAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA529&dq=La+vie+de+Gargantua+et+de+Pantagruel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSj_Cp8ZfPAhUqD8AKHdZgDN0Q6AEISzAH#v=onepage&q=poils%20du%20chien&f=false|page=Chapter XLVI}}</ref> literally translated by [[Peter Anthony Motteux|Motteux]] in the late 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rabelais|first=|title=[[Gargantua and Pantagruel]] Book 5|date=1694|page=Chapter XLVI}}</ref>

==In other languages==
The phrase also exists in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], where the literal translation to English is "(You may cure) the dog's bite with its fur", but has evolved into a short phrase ("kutyaharapást szőrével") that is used frequently in other contexts when one is trying to express that the solution to a problem is more of the problem. Among the [[Irish people|Irish]] and Mexicans, the phrase 'The Cure' ("curarse la cruda", in Spanish) is often used instead of 'hair of the dog'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stevenroyedwards.com/drunkinirish.html |title=How to talk about alcohol in the Republic of Ireland |publisher=Stevenroyedwards.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref> It is used, often sarcastically, in the question "Going for a Cure?"  In Costa Rica (Central America), the same expression is used but it refers to a pig as in: hair of the same pig ("pelos de la misma chancha" in Central America) referring to the same method to cure the hangover.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

In some Slavic languages (Polish, Bosnian, Bulgarian, Croatian, Serbian, Slovenian and Russian), hair of the dog is called "a wedge" (''klin''), mirroring the concept of dislodging a stuck wedge with another one; hence the popular Polish phrase "[to dislodge] a wedge [with] a wedge"  &ndash; ''[wybijać] klin klinem'' &ndash; which is used figuratively both with regard to alcohol and in other contexts. In [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], the phrase is "Клин клин избива". The proper Russian term is [[:wikt:ru:опохмелка|опохмелка]] (opohmelka, "after being drunk"), which indicates a process of drinking to decrease effects of drinking the day before.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

In German, drinking alcohol the next morning to relieve the symptoms is sometimes described as "having a counter-beer" (ein Konterbier trinken), whereas in Austria people talk about having a repair-beer (Reparatur-Seidl). In Portuguese, people speak of "a hit" (uma rebatida), meaning to strike away (the hangover with more alcohol).{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

A similar usage is encountered in [[Romanian language|Romanian]], in the phrase "Cui pe cui se scoate" (''A nail (fastener) pulls out a nail''); in  [[Italian language|Italian]], in the phrase "Chiodo schiaccia chiodo"; in  [[Spanish language|Spanish]], in the phrase "Un clavo saca otro clavo" (''A nail pulls out another nail''); and in [[Turkish language|Turkish]], in the phrase "Çivi çiviyi söker". In all five cases, the English translation is "a nail dislodges a nail", though these phrases are not exclusively used to refer to the hangover cure.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

In Swedish, drinking alcohol to relieve a hangover is called having an "''återställare''", which translates roughly to "restorer". In Norwegian, it is usually called "repareringspils", meaning a "beer to repair". In Finnish, it is called "tasoittava" (smoothening) or "korjaussarja" (repair kit) and in Czech "vyprošťovák" (extricator). In Tanzania, the equivalent Swahili phrase used is "kuzimua" which means 'assist to wake up after a coma'.

In Danish, a beer the day after drinking, is called a "reparationsbajer", which translates to "repair beer". There is also a saying: "One must rise at the tree where one fell".{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}

In Korea, alcohol (typically soju) drunk in the morning to relieve hangovers is called "haejangsul."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dic.daum.net/word/view.do?wordid=kew000082425&q=%ED%95%B4%EC%9E%A5%EC%88%A0 |language=Korean |title=해장술 |publisher=Kumsung Publishing Co. |year=2010}}</ref>

In China, alcohol drunk to relieve hangover is called "回魂酒", literally translates to "the drink that brings back your soul".<ref>{{cite web|title=回魂酒有用嗎？醫：僅限於酒精成癮者|url=http://www.healthnews.com.tw/readnews.php?id=11947|website=健康醫療網|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref>The phrase also exists in (Cheng) Swahili Slang: In Kenya taking alcohol to relieve a hangover is called " Kutoa Lock" Translated into "removing the Lock"

==Scientific background==
There are at least two hypotheses as to how "hair of the dog" works:

In the first, hangovers are described as the first stage of alcohol withdrawal, which is then alleviated by further alcohol intake. Although  "...Low [ethanol] doses may effectively prevent alcohol withdrawal syndrome in surgical patients",<ref>{{EMedicine|article|819502|Withdrawal Syndromes|treatment}}</ref> this idea is questionable as the signs and symptoms of hangover and alcohol withdrawal are very different.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wiese |first1=Jeffrey G. |last2=Shlipak |first2=Michael G. |last3=Browner |first3=Warren S. |title=The Alcohol Hangover |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=132 |issue=11 |pages=897–902 |year=2000 |pmid=10836917 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-132-11-200006060-00008 }}</ref>

In the second, hangovers are attributed to [[methanol]] metabolism.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=A. W. |title=Elimination Half-life of Methanol During Hangover |journal=Pharmacology & Toxicology |volume=60 |issue=3 |pages=217–20 |year=1987 |pmid=3588516 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0773.1987.tb01737.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Calder |first1=Ian |title=Hangovers: Not the ethanol—perhaps the methanol |journal=BMJ |volume=314 |issue=7073 |pages=2–3 |year=1997 |pmid=9001463 |pmc=2125562 |doi=10.1136/bmj.314.7073.2 }}</ref> Levels of methanol, present as a [[Congener (alcohol)|congener]] in alcohol, have been correlated with severity of hangover<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chapman |first1=Loring F. |title=Experimental induction of hangover |journal=Quarterly Journal of Studies on Alcohol |volume=5 |issue=Suppl 5 |pages=67–86 |year=1970 |pmid=5450666 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pawan |first1=GL |title=Alcoholic drinks and hangover effects |journal=The Proceedings of the Nutrition Society |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=15A |year=1973 |pmid=4760771 }}</ref> and methanol metabolism to the highly toxic formate via formaldehyde<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Marx |first1=Christopher J. |last2=Van Dien |first2=Stephen J. |last3=Lidstrom |first3=Mary E. |title=Flux Analysis Uncovers Key Role of Functional Redundancy in Formaldehyde Metabolism |journal=PLoS Biology |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=e16 |year=2005 |pmid=15660163 |pmc=539335 |doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.0030016 }}</ref> coincides with the rate of appearance of hangover symptoms.<ref>Ylikahri RH, Huttunen M, Eriksson CJ, Nikkila EA. Metabolic studies on the pathogenesis of hangover. ''Eur J Clin Invest'' 1974;4:93–100</ref> As both ethanol and methanol are metabolised by alcohol dehydrogenase – and ethanol is a much better substrate for this enzyme – drinking more of the former then effectively prevents (or delays) the metabolism of the latter. As pure ethanol consumption has also been found to increase endogenous levels of methanol,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bendtsen |first1=Preben |last2=Jones |first2=A. Wayne |last3=Helander |first3=Anders |title=Urinary excretion of methanol and 5-hydroxytryptophol as biochemical markers of recent drinking in the hangover state |journal=Alcohol and Alcoholism |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=431–8 |year=1998 |pmid=9719404 |url=http://alcalc.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=9719404 |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.alcalc.a008415}}</ref> presumably for this reason, this suggests that if "hair of the dog" works in this way it effects a temporary hiatus rather than a cure.{{clarify|date=March 2012}}

